♪ Adrift,
I've got no home ♪

11:29.422 --> 11:31.090
♪ Up all too late ♪

11:31.123 --> 11:33.092
♪ So painless I roam ♪

11:33.125 --> 11:36.796
♪ Copin' and dealin'
the best that I can ♪

11:36.829 --> 11:40.700
♪ Because I'm a big bad
travelin' man ♪

11:40.733 --> 11:45.071
Reedus:
These days when people think
Brooklyn, they think hipsters.

11:45.104 --> 11:48.741
♪ I forget what city I'm in ♪

11:48.774 --> 11:50.910
But not too long ago,
it was all warehouses

11:50.943 --> 11:54.046
and hard edges,
and there are still pockets

11:54.080 --> 11:56.716
where you can see
the past peeking through.

11:56.749 --> 11:58.551
Those are the best places
for a bike shop.

11:58.584 --> 12:00.119
♪ Aimless, I roam ♪

12:00.152 --> 12:01.620
♪ Hoping and... ♪

12:01.654 --> 12:03.823
So I'm on my way
to Vax Moto in Gowanus.

12:03.856 --> 12:08.094
♪ I'm a big bad
travelin' man ♪

12:08.127 --> 12:11.197
♪ A big bad travelin' man ♪

12:12.531 --> 12:14.233
What's up, man?
How's it goin'?

12:14.266 --> 12:16.302
Are you Dustin? Hey.
Norman. Nice to see you, man.

12:16.335 --> 12:17.937
-All is well?
-Everything's good.

12:17.970 --> 12:19.271
Yeah. A little nippy.
But it's good.

12:19.305 --> 12:20.940
This place is awesome.
-Yeah. Thank you.

12:20.973 --> 12:23.175
You've got a ton of bikes
in here.
Ton of bikes.

12:23.209 --> 12:25.978
There's about 200 plus bikes
in here right now.

12:27.913 --> 12:29.515
Do you work on
people's bikes here,

12:29.548 --> 12:30.850
or let them work
on their own?

12:30.883 --> 12:32.485
We do.
It's a 24-hour kind

12:32.518 --> 12:34.019
of community-based
garage.

12:34.053 --> 12:35.688
Well, how'd you get
into this?

12:35.721 --> 12:38.357
I -- I grew up with motorcycles
out on Long Island.

12:38.390 --> 12:40.226
And, uh, like
the best things in life,

12:40.259 --> 12:41.994
you know, they're not
kind of planned.

12:42.027 --> 12:43.496
They just sort of happen.
-Yeah, yeah.

12:43.529 --> 12:44.830
And here we are.

12:44.864 --> 12:47.800
♪♪

12:47.833 --> 12:49.268
Which one's yours?

12:49.301 --> 12:51.670
Mine are scattered
throughout the entire place.

12:51.704 --> 12:54.607
Somebody donated this to me,
'82 Beamer.

12:54.640 --> 12:56.442
This is my shovel.
-What's Vax?

12:56.475 --> 12:58.010
My two sons,
Van and Jax.

12:58.043 --> 12:59.979
-Oh, cool.
-Yeah.

13:00.012 --> 13:01.680
It's very important
for these guys

13:01.714 --> 13:04.150
to feel like they're
kind of part of it.

13:04.183 --> 13:06.519
I bartended for
a very long time,

13:06.552 --> 13:08.854
and every time, you would
walk through the door,

13:08.888 --> 13:11.957
I would know your name,
so I try to do that here.

13:11.991 --> 13:14.894
It's great.
That's how it should be.
<b></b>
[Laughter]

13:14.927 --> 13:17.563
I might store somethin' here
sometime if that's cool.
Sure.

13:17.596 --> 13:19.465
Yeah, sure.

13:19.498 --> 13:21.734
Wanna eat?

13:21.767 --> 13:25.004
♪♪

13:27.673 --> 13:29.675
Yeah!

13:29.708 --> 13:31.043
Hi.
Nice to meet you.

13:31.076 --> 13:32.678
How did you guys meet?

13:32.711 --> 13:35.014
Justin: Everything's sort of
bike-related. Mutual friend.

13:35.047 --> 13:37.316
I have a pretty substantial
background in food,
Yeah.

13:37.349 --> 13:40.753
and it just sort of developed
into a food cart.

13:40.786 --> 13:43.055
-We're married now.
-Bosom buddies, right?

13:43.088 --> 13:44.824
Ebony and Ivory.
-Right. I love it.

13:44.857 --> 13:46.525
-Exactly.
-I bet this place is, like,

13:46.559 --> 13:48.561
poppin' in the summer.
There must be people --

13:48.594 --> 13:50.763
This will be
the first summer, you know.
<b></b>
Oh, really? Oh, right on.

13:50.796 --> 13:52.765
So, look into the camera
and tell everyone to come here.

13:52.798 --> 13:55.234
This place will be popping
in the summer. Come here.

13:55.267 --> 13:57.169
What a cool spot this is.
-It is, you know.

13:57.203 --> 13:59.371
It's a weird thing
taking something

13:59.405 --> 14:01.373
that you're passionate about
and turning it into

14:01.407 --> 14:03.042
a working scenario,
you know.

14:03.075 --> 14:04.710
Good for you, man.
Right on.

14:04.743 --> 14:06.111
Thanks.
Bikes, simple.

14:06.145 --> 14:08.347
Bikes and tacos, dude.

14:08.380 --> 14:09.782
Damn! This is awesome.

14:09.815 --> 14:11.517
Nice.
Glad you like it. Yeah.

14:11.550 --> 14:13.953
Do you spend a lot
of time in New York?

14:13.986 --> 14:15.754
Yeah, man. I have
a place in Chinatown.

14:15.788 --> 14:18.090
Nice. We have
a '74 Airstream

14:18.123 --> 14:19.592
that we keep up
in Rhinebeck.

14:19.625 --> 14:22.094
-Oh! Right on.
-So this world alone

14:22.127 --> 14:23.896
is a little bit
overwhelming sometimes.

14:23.929 --> 14:25.965
Even the smallest
little sliver

14:25.998 --> 14:28.234
of something
with trees and grass,

14:28.267 --> 14:30.703
it makes
a huge difference.

14:30.736 --> 14:32.438
Well, we should go
for a ride and --

14:32.471 --> 14:34.440
and work it off somewhere.
Yeah?

14:36.909 --> 14:38.410
Ah, this couldn't be
a better day.

14:38.444 --> 14:40.446
Yeah.

14:40.479 --> 14:43.148
[Kristin Diable's "Billy Wants
to be a Rock N' Roll Star"
plays]

14:43.182 --> 14:45.918
♪ Billy wants to be
a rock 'n' roll star ♪

14:45.951 --> 14:49.321
♪ He's movin' fast,
hittin' tough, workin' hard ♪

14:49.355 --> 14:51.891
Reedus: Justin and I are riding
the Belt Parkway

14:51.924 --> 14:54.560
to the end of Brooklyn,
Coney Island.

14:54.593 --> 14:56.295
It's not exactly
trees and grass,

14:56.328 --> 14:57.930
but it's a place
with cool ocean air

14:57.963 --> 15:01.066
and a touch of the bizarre.

15:01.100 --> 15:03.068
I don't get to do
this very often.

15:03.102 --> 15:05.804
It's amazing, you know,
when you live somewhere,

15:05.838 --> 15:07.106
like, when's the last time

15:07.139 --> 15:08.841
you were on
the Empire State Building?

15:08.874 --> 15:11.410
First time I ever
did it was last year.

15:11.443 --> 15:14.346
♪♪

15:18.517 --> 15:20.519
When was the last time
you were out here?

15:20.552 --> 15:21.921
Ten years ago
or somethin'.

15:21.954 --> 15:24.256
Oh, it's definitely changed
a little bit.

15:24.290 --> 15:26.292
♪♪

15:26.325 --> 15:27.660
Coney Island was once

15:27.693 --> 15:29.862
the country's biggest
amusement park,

15:29.895 --> 15:31.997
beach, rides, boardwalk.

15:32.031 --> 15:33.732
Man: New York's off
to good old fun,

15:33.766 --> 15:36.035
anything to beat the heat.

15:36.068 --> 15:39.772
Reedus: It was a wonderful world
only a short ride away.

15:39.805 --> 15:41.373
It's gone through
its up and downs,

15:41.407 --> 15:43.442
but seeing the rides
come into view,

15:43.475 --> 15:46.278
I can't help
but feel transported.

15:46.312 --> 15:47.646
The Cyclone's violent.

15:47.680 --> 15:49.715
It's a lot of bumps
and bruises.

15:49.748 --> 15:51.550
Yeah. I love it.

15:51.583 --> 15:54.553
♪♪

15:54.586 --> 15:56.288
Wow. It's a ghost town.

15:56.322 --> 15:59.325
♪♪

16:00.926 --> 16:04.196
They are trying
down here.
Yeah.

16:04.229 --> 16:06.332
They've retained a lot
of what it was

16:06.365 --> 16:11.236
and freshened up what needed
to not be here anymore.

16:11.270 --> 16:12.905
What is this
orange thing?

16:12.938 --> 16:14.974
That used to be, like,
a parachute ride.

16:15.007 --> 16:17.576
[Riders screaming]

16:17.609 --> 16:19.845
I love this -- the smiley face
right here. It's awesome.

16:19.878 --> 16:21.914
Justin: This is the greatest
branding in the world.

16:21.947 --> 16:24.249
-It's so psycho.
-It's got to be terrifying

16:24.283 --> 16:26.085
for a little small kid
though, no?

16:26.118 --> 16:28.787
Right?

16:28.821 --> 16:31.390
Should we get our photos
made on a t-shirt?

16:31.423 --> 16:34.360
-Absolutely.
-Right.

16:34.393 --> 16:35.928
What's the border?
-Any one you like.

16:35.961 --> 16:38.097
"Homies forever."

16:38.130 --> 16:39.498
Homies forever.

16:39.531 --> 16:41.367
Let's do homies forever.
Yeah. Here, I got it.

16:41.400 --> 16:42.835
I'm just gonna sit
in your lap.

16:42.868 --> 16:44.770
And then just hold me around
the waist like...

16:44.803 --> 16:47.840
Really?
Good lord.

16:47.873 --> 16:49.675
Perfect.
<b></b>
[Laughter]

16:49.708 --> 16:51.577
That's awesome.

16:51.610 --> 16:52.778
Thanks, guys.

16:52.811 --> 16:55.414
These are awesome
right here.

16:55.447 --> 16:56.915
Let's take a look.

16:56.949 --> 16:58.384
Oh, wow.

16:58.417 --> 17:01.520
Look, look, look!
It's showtime, Coney Island!

17:01.553 --> 17:03.188
Join us on the inside
of the world-famous

17:03.222 --> 17:04.890
Coney Island circus sideshow.

17:04.923 --> 17:07.426
We literally scoured the globe
to find the strangest,

17:07.459 --> 17:09.595
most exciting,
most exotic acts we can find

17:09.628 --> 17:11.463
and bring 'em here for you.

17:11.497 --> 17:13.732
And it's right
inside these doors.

17:13.766 --> 17:17.069
♪♪

17:17.102 --> 17:20.305
Oh, my God, dude.
Shut up.

17:20.339 --> 17:22.141
Wow.
Thank you, thank you.

17:22.174 --> 17:24.943
Now, uh, a lot of people
think sword swallowing is fake,

17:24.977 --> 17:27.112
but if you look closely,
you can see what we in the biz

17:27.146 --> 17:30.482
like to call stomach boogers.
That's the bile.

17:30.516 --> 17:33.419
Now, Norman,
come on up here.

17:33.452 --> 17:36.221
I'm gonna bend forward to you.
I'm gonna give you a signal.

17:36.255 --> 17:37.790
You grab the handle
of the saw

17:37.823 --> 17:40.826
and just pull it
straight out of my body.

17:40.859 --> 17:42.094
What?

17:42.127 --> 17:43.729
All right, Norman.
Are you ready?

17:43.762 --> 17:45.164
Yeah.

17:45.197 --> 17:48.500
♪♪

17:55.808 --> 17:57.643
Dude.
-There you have it.

17:57.676 --> 17:59.745
That's for the home video.

17:59.778 --> 18:02.448
You know what was nuts
is I could feel the
guh-guh-guh-guh-guh.

18:02.481 --> 18:04.983
You can feel the ridges kind of
in the sides of my throat.
<b></b>
Yeah.

18:05.017 --> 18:07.786
-Dude, that's crazy.
-Now, since you're up here,

18:07.820 --> 18:10.756
the Coney Island
torture chair.

18:10.789 --> 18:12.091
We are the last full-time

18:12.124 --> 18:14.426
10-in-one sideshow
in the world.

18:14.460 --> 18:17.362
You're gonna have 10,000
or so volts of electricity

18:17.396 --> 18:18.697
coursing
through your system.

18:18.730 --> 18:20.199
The thing I really love about it

18:20.232 --> 18:23.202
is everything
in the sideshow is real.

18:23.235 --> 18:25.037
Unlike magic,
there is no illusion.

18:25.070 --> 18:26.371
Norman Reedus,
any last words?

18:26.405 --> 18:28.040
Someone
take care of my cat.

18:28.073 --> 18:30.642
Before, a lot of people
wouldn't come to the freak show.

18:30.676 --> 18:33.212
There was this stigma
that it was gonna be creepy.

18:33.245 --> 18:35.314
But no. These people
are talented.

18:35.347 --> 18:37.149
♪♪

18:37.182 --> 18:39.918
A one, a two, and a...

18:41.386 --> 18:44.156
Whoa.

18:44.189 --> 18:46.959
That was awesome.
-Very nice.

18:46.992 --> 18:50.129
♪♪

19:04.009 --> 19:05.911
[Clapping]
[Laughter]

19:05.944 --> 19:08.247
That was so cool.
Does that burn your tongue?

19:08.280 --> 19:10.215
Uh, if you do it wrong.

19:10.249 --> 19:11.750
How did you get
into all this?

19:11.783 --> 19:13.819
After high school,
I got into magic,

19:13.852 --> 19:15.821
and then I just
segued into sideshow.

19:15.854 --> 19:19.925
But when I came out here, I met
a different type of individual

19:19.958 --> 19:21.393
than I had ever met before,

19:21.426 --> 19:23.729
natural-born freaks
as they're referred to,

19:23.762 --> 19:26.265
like, you know, the Lobster Boys
and that sort of thing.
Wow.

19:26.298 --> 19:29.334
It just changes the way
you look at humanity
in general, I think.

19:29.368 --> 19:32.437
Nice. Who does the artwork
up here? It's really cool.

19:32.471 --> 19:35.274
They're all painted
by our artist in residence,

19:35.307 --> 19:36.508
Marie Roberts.

19:38.477 --> 19:41.613
Marie, are you home?
-I'm home. Hi, Ray.

19:41.647 --> 19:43.549
Hi.
-Norman.

19:43.582 --> 19:45.083
-Nice to meet you.
-Nice to meet you.

19:45.117 --> 19:46.952
You let me if they give you
any trouble, okay?

19:46.985 --> 19:48.453
I know.
You have machetes.

19:48.487 --> 19:50.789
-They've seen what I can do.
-Pleasure.

19:50.822 --> 19:52.424
Thank you so much.
-Take care, man.

19:52.457 --> 19:54.126
Wow. What a cool studio
you have.

19:54.159 --> 19:56.295
-Thank you.
-How did you get into this?

19:56.328 --> 19:58.630
-I ran away from the sideshow.
-Really?

19:58.664 --> 20:00.566
My Uncle Lester
was the talker

20:00.599 --> 20:03.302
at the Dreamland Circus Sideshow
in the 1920s.

20:03.335 --> 20:05.437
♪♪

20:05.470 --> 20:07.039
So I grew up
thinking people

20:07.072 --> 20:09.141
without arms
and legs were normal.

20:09.174 --> 20:11.810
And when I heard
that painting was a career,

20:11.843 --> 20:14.413
I thought, "Wow,
let's can the freak show

20:14.446 --> 20:16.982
and go become an artist."

20:17.015 --> 20:19.318
And then, 20 years ago,
I met Dick Zigun,

20:19.351 --> 20:21.587
who started Coney Island,
USA,

20:21.620 --> 20:23.822
and I brought down
all my Uncle Lester's

20:23.855 --> 20:26.491
sideshow pictures
and memorabilia.

20:26.525 --> 20:28.927
They're photos
of all the freak show,

20:28.961 --> 20:30.429
The Dreamland Freak Show,

20:30.462 --> 20:33.298
eating
at Stauch's Restaurant.

20:33.332 --> 20:35.067
And Dick said,

20:35.100 --> 20:38.904
"It's nice to see that
Lionel the Lion-faced Man

20:38.937 --> 20:41.974
can put on a paper hat
and have fun like anybody else."

20:42.007 --> 20:43.842
And I thought,
"Wow, this organization

20:43.875 --> 20:45.344
is a little bit different,"

20:45.377 --> 20:47.446
except I think
this is all normal.
Yeah.

20:47.479 --> 20:49.114
And what's
out there isn't.

20:49.147 --> 20:51.950
Does that make sense?
-Absolutely.

20:51.984 --> 20:54.353
Reedus: I always think I can't
be amazed any more.

20:54.386 --> 20:56.021
-Thank you so much
for coming up.
-Absolutely.

20:56.054 --> 20:57.756
And then I see places
like these,

20:57.789 --> 20:59.191
and I'm reminded of a magic

20:59.224 --> 21:01.360
that's waiting
behind each new door.

21:01.393 --> 21:04.529
Sideshows have allowed
audiences to confront

21:04.563 --> 21:07.165
and embrace some
of society's taboos.

21:07.199 --> 21:09.701
Dude, thank you.
What a cool guy, dude.
<b></b>
Really appreciate it.
It was great to meet you.

21:09.735 --> 21:11.770
And for me, any art
that can entertain

21:11.803 --> 21:13.538
and open minds,

21:13.572 --> 21:16.108
well, that's what
it's all about.

21:18.744 --> 21:21.713
♪♪

21:21.747 --> 21:23.982
New York City! Yeah!

21:24.016 --> 21:26.885
The sun's setting
on a long day.

21:26.918 --> 21:28.720
Home wouldn't be home
without old friends,

21:28.754 --> 21:30.455
and I'm looking forward
to catching up

21:30.489 --> 21:31.757
with some tomorrow.

21:34.526 --> 21:38.030
Wilson: Doyers Street is,
in the history books,

21:38.063 --> 21:40.232
the street that has
the most murder

21:40.265 --> 21:42.234
on it in America.

21:46.038 --> 21:46.204
[Thunder

21:46.204 --> 21:48.807
[Thunder rumbles]

21:48.840 --> 21:51.543
[Thunder rumbles]

21:53.812 --> 21:55.314
For hundreds of years,

21:55.347 --> 21:58.350
New Yorkers have faced
their challenges head-on

21:58.383 --> 22:00.185
and persevered.

22:03.822 --> 22:06.925
♪♪

22:11.496 --> 22:13.198
Man: You got to have muscle
in your hustle

22:13.231 --> 22:14.499
to really make it in New York,

22:14.533 --> 22:15.967
or it will spit you out.

22:16.001 --> 22:17.803
It will stomp you out.

22:17.836 --> 22:20.739
Man #2: The city is constantly
throwing challenges at people,

22:20.772 --> 22:23.375
and if you are resourceful,

22:23.408 --> 22:25.877
you -- you'll be able
to survive it.

22:27.079 --> 22:28.513
It kicks you in the nuts,

22:28.547 --> 22:32.184
and it gets you down
or just evolve from that.

22:32.217 --> 22:35.721
Stay alive and don't
leave New York City, you know.

22:35.754 --> 22:36.988
That's it.

22:37.022 --> 22:40.392
♪♪

22:49.601 --> 22:51.737
Good morning.

22:51.770 --> 22:53.772
Reedus: I'm heading to one
of my favorite spots

22:53.805 --> 22:56.875
in Little Italy,

22:56.908 --> 22:58.243
a neighborhood
in the center of it all

22:58.276 --> 23:00.712
that's never lost
its Old World charm.

23:00.746 --> 23:03.048
♪♪

23:03.081 --> 23:04.716
Hey, good morning.
-Good morning.

23:04.750 --> 23:06.785
This is my favorite coffee shop
in all of New York.

23:06.818 --> 23:09.721
It's got such a good ambiance,
the old tin ceilings.

23:09.755 --> 23:11.857
My grandfather started
the, uh, place,

23:11.890 --> 23:14.126
been a pastry shop
since 1891.

23:14.159 --> 23:15.727
-Wow.
-Over the years,

23:15.761 --> 23:19.598
we've added a few things like
Wi-Fi and stuff like that.

23:19.631 --> 23:21.600
But, uh, the back bar
is the original back bar

23:21.633 --> 23:24.736
from when the bar was here
before the building was built.
<b></b>
Oh, wow.

23:24.770 --> 23:27.105
♪♪

23:27.139 --> 23:29.775
We must be doin' something right
if we're out here that long.

23:29.808 --> 23:31.243
Buddy, you're killing it.

23:35.914 --> 23:37.516
Yeah, Tony!

23:37.549 --> 23:38.617
How are you, dude?

23:38.650 --> 23:40.051
Nice to see you.

23:40.085 --> 23:41.787
My dear friend, Tony Shafrazi,

23:41.820 --> 23:45.357
he's a gallery owner, art dealer
and a longtime New Yorker.

23:47.692 --> 23:49.227
Have you been here
before?

23:49.261 --> 23:51.329
Yeah,
before you were born.

23:51.363 --> 23:52.464
Really?

23:52.497 --> 23:53.732
I've known him for years,

23:53.765 --> 23:56.601
and seeing him always makes me
feel like I'm back home.

23:56.635 --> 23:58.970
Well, I remember you and Saul,
like, on Green Street.

23:59.004 --> 24:00.605
You were, like, about --
How old were you?

24:00.639 --> 24:02.674
You were about 20 years old,
good-looking guy and...

24:02.707 --> 24:04.776
was
a good-looking guy?

24:04.810 --> 24:06.778
Remember Michael Stipe
had that glam party,

24:06.812 --> 24:09.281
and I put on a --
a see-through slip,

24:09.314 --> 24:11.149
and I was at the party,
like, in a dress.

24:11.183 --> 24:13.485
And then I had to go shoot
the cover of Vanity Fair

24:13.518 --> 24:14.686
the next morning.
-Right.

24:14.719 --> 24:16.688
